# Tailwind CSS Rule

Follow these standards when writing or editing Tailwind CSS classes:

- Prefer utility-first styling directly in markup for component-scoped styles.
- Keep class lists readable: layout -> spacing -> typography -> color -> effects -> state.
- Use responsive variants (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`) mobile-first; avoid redundant overrides.
- Always include interactive states for controls (`hover:`, `focus-visible:`, `disabled:` when relevant).
- Preserve accessible contrast and visible focus indicators.
- Prefer semantic design tokens already in `tailwind.config` (colors, spacing, radius) over arbitrary values.
- Use arbitrary values only when no token fits and the value is justified by the design.
- Extract repeated utility combinations into reusable components or shared helpers instead of duplicating long class strings.
- Avoid conflicting utilities in the same class list (for example multiple `p-*` values unless breakpoint-specific).
- When class logic becomes conditional, use a class-composition helper pattern for clarity.

## Example

```tsx
// Good: clear ordering, responsive behavior, and accessible states
<button className="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-md bg-primary px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white shadow-sm transition-colors hover:bg-primary/90 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-primary/60 disabled:cursor-not-allowed disabled:opacity-50 md:px-5">
  Save
</button>
```
